Anyway, when I play with people long enough and we become closer *friends* ((I consider my in-game friends friends, just as I would those I know in real life)), eventually OOC issues come out.  In these situations I actually like knowing who is behind the avatar, because if it is a guy talking about his boyfriend instead of a girl, that changes my advice to him significantly.  I never ask anyone to reveal RL information, but if they choose too I'm always glad to know it.<br>
<br>
I've met guys playing girls, and girls playing guys to avoid being constantly flirted with.  Yes, there are women who play just to play, not to get themselves involved in inter-personal RP romantic relationships.  ((I've met a few women playing children for this reason, constantly using shrink potions...but guys sometimes hit on them anyway...))  None of this matters to me IC, but OOC RL gender is important.<br>
<br>
This is just my opinion as someone who makes OOC friendships while playing EQ.  Of course if you come on EQ just to play, then of course RL gender should never matter. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=viala>Viala</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 110<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/24/03 10:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3921.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: In the eyes of the FV Community...Id like to know</span><hr size=1> Coming to EQ from a background in tabletop roleplaying, where all of us regularly played other gendered characters as a matter of course, I would at first not have thought anything of a man playing a woman or vice versa in EQ. And I still think that people should be able to do this without adverse comment from other players, unless there was some kind of actual OOC deception going on. <br>
<br>
However, from a personal point of view, I've come to realise that gameplay and RP in EQ can be qualitatively different from the tabletop experience. It's more immersive, it's more ongoing. You spend much more time with your EQ toon than you ever do playing a tabletop RP character, and I've decided that *I personally* prefer to play my own gender.<br>
